CONJUNCTIVITIS, INTERNALLY DISPLACED PERSONS - PAKISTAN (SINDH)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Thu 23 Sep 2010
Source: The Daily Times [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\09\23\story_23-9-2010_pg12_5>


Conjunctivitis has been affecting the internally displaced persons
(IDPs) and other citizens across Sindh, especially in Karachi.
Sources said the IDPs were at a higher risk of being infected with
viral eye infections due to various reasons, especially personal
hygiene, which has yet to be addressed with the provision of toilette goods.

In the past 40 days, the number of IDPs affected with different types
of eye infections, including epidemic conjunctivitis, has reached 11
877, of whom 421 people had reported at 57 medical relief camps
across the city on Tue 21 Sep 2010 alone.

City District Government Karachi Health Executive District Officer Dr
Javed Nasir said viral eye infections have a self-limiting time
course of 5-15 days.

The use of contaminated water is one of the reasons for the spread of
eye infection, he added. Although anti-bacterial chlorine tablets
were added to the water, they need 2 hours to make the water
bacteria-free, he said. Generally, the IDPs do not follow
instructions and start using water before it is free from bacteria
[and viruses], he added.

Sindh Health Minister Dr Sagheer Ahmed had ordered establishment of
11 special eye camps at the city's major hospitals, which have so far
examined 5030 people. 35 patients have been referred to other
hospitals for further treatment, he added.

[Byline: Irfan Aligi]

