[Conjunctivitis is an inflammation or infection of the thin layer
(conjunctiva) that lines the inside of the eyelid and covers the
white part of the eye. Inflammation can cause blood vessels in the
eye to become larger. And that can make the white of the eye look
pink or red. Conjunctivitis is a common health condition worldwide.
The 3 most common types of conjunctivitis are viral, bacterial, and
allergic. Currently, outbreaks are occurring throughout the world
(see ProMED-mail references below), and not surprisingly, the extent
of the outbreak in disaster-struck Pakistan far exceeds that observed
elsewhere. A viral etiology is presumed in most of these outbreaks,
but in no case has this been confirmed unequivocally. In view of the
ubiquity of conjunctivitis, in future, outbreaks will be reported
only where the etiologic agent or agents have been identified.

A map of the provinces of Pakistan showing the location of Karachi in
Sindh province can be accessed at:
<http://www.asiawaves.net/pakistan-map.htm>. The
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Pakistan is available at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00tj>. - Mod.CP]
